<TEXT>
former rep gladys noon spellman died early 
sunday in a suburban maryland nursing home at age 70 she had been 
in a coma for nearly eight years 
mrs spellman a democrat who represented maryland in congress 
was headed for reelection to her fourth term in the house when her 
heart stopped beating temporarily on oct 31 1980 while she was 
judging a halloween costume contest at a shopping mall 
four days later she was reelected to congress with 80 percent 
of the vote over littleknown republican kevin r igoe 
mrs spellman remained hospitalized in critical condition for 
several weeks following her heart attack but her condition later 
stabilized and she was able to breath without the aid of 
lifesupport equipment 
she never regained consciousness 
after receiving a medical analysis stating that mrs spellman 
was in a trancelike state and unable to take the oath of 
office the house declared her seat vacant in february 1981 
it was the first time the house vacated the seat of a member who 
had become mentally or physically disabled 
thirtytwo republican and democratic candidates including mrs 
spellmans husband reuben entered a special primary on april 7 
1981 to select the nominees to run for election in marylands 
fifth district 
spellman was defeated for the democratic nomination by steny 
hoyer who went on to defeat audrey scott the gop mayor of bowie 
md in a special election held may 19 1981 hoyer continues to 
serve in the house 
sen barbara mikulski dmd recalled sunday that mrs spellman 
was assigned as a big sister to help acquaint her with the 
workings of congress when she arrived in 1977 
after an hour and a half i felt like an old hand after being 
in gladys spellmans hands ms mikulski said 
i thought gladys spellman was great she continued she 
knew how to respond to the daytoday needs of her constituents 
she was probably one of the best maryland public servants in terms 
of constituent services 
ruth davis a longtime friend who was mrs spellmans office 
manager said mrs spellman died at 1230 am on sunday she died 
at the hebrew home of greater washington in rockville md 
born in new york city on march 2 1918 as gladys noon mrs 
spellman was educated in washington dc public schools and 
attended george washington university and the graduate school of 
the department of agriculture 
her first elected position was as a member of the prince 
georges county board of commissioners in 1962 in 1967 she was 
appointed by president johnson to the advisory commission on 
intergovernmental relations 
she was first elected to congress in november 1974 
she is survived by her husband and three children stephen 
louis richard eric and dana spellman oneill in addition to four 
grandchildren 
</TEXT>
