<TEXT>
oscar h davis a judge for the us circuit 
court of appeals for the federal circuit died sunday at the age of 
74 
davis died of cancer at george washington university hospital 
he was named to the us court of claims in 1962 and was chief 
judge during the 1970s 
davis was named to the appeals bench six years ago following a 
federal court reorganization that abolished the court of claims and 
set up a new federal circuit of the us court of appeals 
he was a native of new york city and served with the army air 
forces during world war ii a harvard university graduate in 1934 
davis was a 1937 graduate of columbia university law school 
he joined the justice departments claims division in 1939 after 
practicing law in new york city for two years davis joined the 
solicitor generals office in 1949 and was named first assistant 
to the solicitor general in 1954 he held that post until becoming 
an associate judge on the court of claims 
davis argued more than 50 cases before the us supreme court 
during his tenure in the solicitor generals office and 
participated in work involving the tafthartley act 
</TEXT>
