<TEXT>
when the grand tour a musical based on sn 
behrmans play jacobowsky and the colonel opened on broadway 
in 1979 it was overproduced and undernourished 
the story of the friendship between a likable everresourceful 
jew and an aristocratic antisemitic polish army officer often was 
swallowed up by the shows lavish production how could it compete 
with a fullscale automobile that trundled across the stage 
singing nuns an elaborate railroad car a chorus of exuberant 
hasidim a gargantuan flag of poland that served as the focal point 
of a big dance number and a colorful circus scene the show died 
in two months 
now a streamlined and much simpler version of the grand tour 
has opened at offbroadways jewish repertory theater the result 
is an absolute delight a show brimming with tuneful songs and a 
touching funny and immensely human story that is finally allowed 
to shine its a joyful revival on par with last seasons engaging 
resurrection of flora the red menace another musical 
obscurity 
the transformation in the grand tour from more to less has 
been startling director ran avni makes do with two wooden 
turntables for the set designed by jeffrey schneider gone are the 
nuns and the polish flag the automobile is conjured out of a few 
pieces of wood and a turntable the circus atmosphere has been 
reduced to a few colored pennants 
what expands into this spartan atmosphere is the plot and 
characters jacobowsky and the colonel band together to flee the 
nazis as they advance through the french countryside in 1940 they 
are accompanied by the colonels french girlfriend who inevitably 
becomes the focal point in a love triangle 
the revival with a revised book by michael stewart and mark 
bramble puts these three people back in focus the story of their 
journey to freedom is important but it doesnt surplant their 
growing affection for each other 
that affection is expressed in hermans music which piles melody 
on top of melody its a dizzying display of song the evening 
starts with jacobowskys entrance number ill be here 
tomorrow a survivors song worthy of dolly levi or mame dennis 
but there are several other number particularly marianne a 
haunting love song for the colonel and i belong here 
mariannes hymn to home that deserve to be heard again 
joel grey was the original jacobowsky in the grand tour 
stuart zagnit is his worthy successor here its a performance that 
straddles a very difficult line zagnit is able to be appealing 
without descending into cloying cuteness and hes got one of those 
terrific musical comedy voices that makes every lyric count 
zagnit has a worthy opponent and finally friend in paul 
ukena jr who turns the colonel into someone more than a buffoon 
patricia ben peterson who plays marianne manages to make the 
woman into more than a bone of contention between the two men 
the show succeeds this time around because it has taken the 
trouble to care about its characters and now so does the 
audience the grand tour is a grand musical comedy a worthy 
journey for anyone to take 
</TEXT>
